description:
## Problem

`wai reflect` fails inside Claude Code with:

    ◆ Proposed changes:
      CLAUDE.md
    + wai::agent-mode
    Error:   × not connected

Root cause: `src/commands/reflect.rs` calls `backend.complete(prompt)` but does not handle the `AGENT_SENTINEL` return value. When `detect_backend` selects `AgentBackend` (because `CLAUDECODE` is set), the sentinel `"wai::agent-mode"` is returned as the content and then used literally as the WAI:REFLECT block content — which is wrong.

## How `wai why` Does It

`src/commands/why.rs` (line ~1088) checks for the sentinel after calling `backend.complete()`:

```rust
Ok(r) if r == AGENT_SENTINEL => {
    // Agent backend wrote context to stdout; no further output needed.
    println!("  {} Context sent to your agent", "○".dimmed());
    return Ok(());
}
```

`AgentBackend::complete()` prints the `[AGENT CONTEXT]...[/AGENT CONTEXT]` block to stdout (where Claude Code reads it), then returns the sentinel. The surrounding agent (Claude) reads the context block and responds inline.

## Fix

In `src/commands/reflect.rs`, after calling `backend.complete(prompt)`, add a sentinel check matching the `wai why` pattern:

```rust
let raw = backend.complete(prompt).map_err(...)?;
if raw == AGENT_SENTINEL {
    // Context printed to stdout by AgentBackend; Claude Code will respond.
    // The agent's response needs to be captured and injected into CLAUDE.md.
    // See wai why's agent flow for the pattern.
    return Ok(());
}
```

Note: unlike `wai why` (which just prints the answer), `reflect` needs the LLM response in order to write the WAI:REFLECT block. The agent flow for `reflect` will need to prompt Claude to output the block in a structured way that can be captured and injected — or `reflect` needs to display the context block and instruct the user/agent to paste the result back via `wai reflect --content "..."`.

## References

- `src/llm.rs` — `AgentBackend`, `AGENT_SENTINEL`, `detect_backend`, `format_agent_output`
- `src/commands/why.rs:1088` — sentinel handling in why
- `src/commands/reflect.rs:567` — where the backend call happens

In src/managed_block.rs, add a note after the bd ready step in "Starting a Session", gated on has_beads:

  if has_beads {
      block.push_str(
          "   Before claiming: read the relevant source files to confirm\n\
           \x20  the issue is not already implemented.\n",
      );
  }

Note: second line must use exactly 3 spaces of indent (\x20 + 2 spaces), matching the spec string.

Unit tests:
- 3.2: wai_block_content(&["beads"]) → output contains "already implemented" near the bd ready line
- 3.3: wai_block_content(&[]) → no "already implemented" text

Epic: wai-h2li
Openspec ref: add-managed-block-openspec-checklist:3.1-3.3

In src/managed_block.rs, add a conditional push_str inside the "Ending a Session" block, after the beads steps and before wai reflect:

  if has_openspec {
      block.push_str(
          "[ ] openspec tasks.md — mark completed tasks [x]\n",
      );
  }

Unit tests:
- 1.2: wai_block_content(&["openspec"]) → output contains "openspec tasks.md"
- 1.3: wai_block_content(&[]) → output does NOT contain "openspec tasks.md"
- 1.4: ordering — openspec tasks.md line appears after bd sync --from-main (if beads present) and before wai reflect

Epic: wai-h2li
